# THE SHARED WIRING-TEST REVISION THIS REPOSITORY ADOPTED, BY CONTENT.
#
# tests/test_release_wiring.sh and tests/test_wiring_mutations.sh are
# not this repository's work. They are ~1000 lines COPIED from the
# compiler repository's fleet/templates/, of which everything outside
# the CONFIG markers is meant to be byte-identical across every adopter.
# Nothing noticed when a copy diverged, which has already happened twice
# in this fleet: a capability tuple hand-copied at 21 sites that had
# already drifted, and check_tag_version.sh becoming a second copy whose
# two versions immediately printed different messages.
#
# So this file records the SHA-256 of each file's shared region, and
# tests/test_shared_regions.sh checks it two ways:
#
#   1. OFFLINE, by digesting the local files and comparing. This never
#      skips, and it catches the ordinary case, an edit below the line.
#   2. ONLINE, by fetching the canonical template at the revision named
#      below and digesting THAT with the same code. Layer 1 compares a
#      file in this repository against a number in this repository, so
#      anyone who edits the body can regenerate the number and go green.
#      Layer 2 is what makes the number honest. It reports SKIP without
#      `gh`, matching tests/test_release_wiring.sh.
#
# THE `revision` LINE BELOW IS NOT THE GUARD PIN. .github/guard-pins.sha256
# has its own, and the two are deliberately independent: a single shared
# revision would make every guard bump force a wiring re-audit and every
# wiring bump force a guard re-audit, and that friction is the likeliest
# reason for either audit to be skipped altogether.
#
# TO ADOPT: replace the placeholder revision with the compiler commit you
# copied the templates from, and the digests with that commit's
# fleet/shared-regions.sha256. Then run
#
#   bash tests/test_shared_regions.sh
#
# and expect it green with layer 2 confirming the numbers, not skipping.
#
# TO RE-ADOPT AFTER A TEMPLATE CHANGE: read the diff between the two
# revisions, re-copy both files, keep your CONFIG blocks, then update
# the revision and the digests together. Updating the digests without
# re-copying is how a local edit becomes a permanent fork with a green
# test over it.

